After capturing the pawn, I'll aim to keep my king active and central, potentially seeking opportunities for stalemate or a fortress position.

White's knight on b5 stands out as a target. It appears to be undefended, so attacking it would gain a tempo. Also, I should be looking to complete my development and potentially continue with kingside castling.

- a7a6 would immediately attack the knight, forcing it to retreat
- f4e5 would centralize my bishop
- g8f8 would connect my rooks

- Moving to e4 could put me on a diagonal with the white bishop on b2
- Moving to c6 looks strong as it maintains distance from the white king while moving toward my pawn on a4
- Moving to c4 is also reasonable, heading toward my a-pawn from below

I'll choose c6, which keeps me safe from the bishop's diagonal, maintains king opposition, and moves toward supporting my a-pawn.
